{"key":"post-11690925","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11690925</id>\n<content>The black and white pipes are at the end of the fruiting area, and stick vertically from the ceiling through the soil to the air above.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Air will flow any time there's a temperature or pressure difference.&amp;nbsp; Nature hates a vacuum or anything out of equilibrium, such as different temperatures at each end of a pipe.&amp;nbsp; Considering that it's almost always a different temperature under ground than above, there is constant passive air flow in and out of the container.&amp;nbsp; I control the flow by blocking off part of the pipes to restrict it during winter to keep temperatures above freezing.&amp;nbsp; Time will tell if I'll still get rid of enough CO2 once I get it fully loaded.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;During summer, there was always a noticeable wind coming from the pipes, and the temperature stayed a steady 60F inside.&amp;nbsp; Now that it's been below 0F outside for two months, the temperature has dropped to the high 40s, which is still fine for oyster mushrooms.&amp;nbsp;  I suspect this temp drop is related more to not getting the rest of the excavation work done before winter set in hard.&amp;nbsp; Next spring, there will be an extra three to eight feet of soil piled on top of the container, returning the hillside to original grade.&amp;nbsp; This will keep the freezing level well above the farm.&amp;nbsp; The ground here is frozen about four to five feet deep at present.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition to the two large pipes leaving the fruiting area, there are two 2&quot; PVC pipes that serve as drains from the concrete tank filled with rocks.&amp;nbsp; These also allow a backflow of fresh air, and I can always feel a slight breeze coming up out of the rocks from that area.&amp;nbsp; Once the farm is full of fruiting substrates, I'll monitor the CO2 and if necessary, install a wind powered turbine(like you see on roofs to vent the attic) on one of the roof vents.&amp;nbsp; I put one on this summer, but took it back off for winter because it moved so much air.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11690953</next>\n<prev>11690889</prev>\n<first>11681761</first>\n<last>13673392</last>\n<when>1261409111</when>\n<utime>12/21/09 05:25 PM</utime>\n</post>"}